observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and the management agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant to:
prepare JEV to re-classify the projects that are still on-going;
prepare JEV to correct the misclassification of PPE to another account;
prepare the JEV to correct the erroneous recognition and non-recognition of PPE account;
ensure that depreciation is properly provided for each class of PPE as discussed in PAG3 of the IPSAS 17 and provide for the detailed schedule of depreciation;
prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account.
The General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office.
The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities, conduct and complete the physical inventory in three months or less and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended, and the management agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary adjusting entry to close the cost of inventory and correct the balance of the Trust Liabilities- DRRM account;
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to initiate the reconciliation of records covering the periods CY 2019 to CY 2023 and should arrive at the correct balance of the unspent portion of the DRRM Fund and moving forward, to implement regular reconciliation particularly at year end;
The Municipal Accountant to conduct thorough investigation on the transferred fund from the DRRM bank account to the trust fund bank account representing the cost in conducting the Contingency Plan Formulation Training and draw the needed adjusting journal entry;
The members of the Local Finance Committee to reconcile their respective records and come up with a validated and revised LDRRM Fund Utilization Report and initiate the setting up and the actual transfer of the unspent portion of the CY 2024 LDRRMF; and
The Municipal Accountant to provide corrective measures in monitoring the special trust fund and incorporate such corrections to the LDRRM Fund Utilization Report.

We recommended, and the management agreed to:
Instruct the members of the Local Finance Committee to exert efforts in ensuring regular reconciliation of financial records and reports, and strengthen internal control systems;
Order the members of the Local Finance Committee to ensure that all savings to be declared by the Municipality are duly supported with actual funds;
Call for a special meeting with the members of the local finance committee to tackle financial restructuring to rectify the cash deficits incurred by the municipality; and
Declare AO No. 1, series of 2024 illegal.

We recommended, and the management agreed to:
Call for a special meeting with the members of the Local Finance Committee to discuss financial restructuring and provide resolution on the shortage of cash in order to continue the implementation of projects funded by the continuing appropriation;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to fast track the completion of the ten remaining development projects;
Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to closely monitor the budget appropriations and obligations of the 20% DF and ensure the correctness of the prepared SAAOB; and
Instruct the members of the Local Finance Committee to prepare and submit a duly verified FUR, and the same be posted at the DILF FDPP website and in at least three conspicuous public places.

We recommended, and the management agreed to:
Inform Local Sanggunian to declare AO No. 5, s. of 2023 inoperative and make the necessary adjustments to correct the deficiency, and the revised budget be submitted for approval before it can be implemented;
Inform the MDRRMC and the Local Sanggunian to plan out new expenditure items charged to the CY 2023 unexpended balance amounting to ₱1,009,255.17, and ensure its inclusion in the LDRRM Investment Plan;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that only those expenditures consistent with the approved budget and disaster risk reduction and management related PPAs be charged against the 5% LDRRMF; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit a revised 5% LDRRMF Utilization Report duly validated by the Municipal Budget Officer and the LDRRMO as to the accuracy of the report, and initiate the transfer of the CY 2024 unexpended balance to the DRRM bank account.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct:
The Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to verify and ensure that all programs and projects implemented financed by the FY 2022 LGSF-GEF are incorporated in the DTP and AIP;
The Local Finance Committee composed of the Local Budget Officer, Local Treasurer, Local Planning and Development Coordinator to prepare and submit the Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project Implementation;
The Municipal Treasurer to verify the accuracy of the undisbursed balance and consequently issue payment to revert the undisbursed balance to the National Treasury; and 
The Municipal Accountant to submit the DVs with complete supporting documents and exercise prudence in allowing the payment to contractors despite incomplete documents.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to:
Prepare JEV to correct the entries made on the purchase of equipment not recorded as asset and ensure that all government property officially received by the Municipality are accounted for and taken up in the books;
Prepare JEV to capitalized the cost of delivery of the heavy equipment;
Prepare JEV to adjust the properties below the capitalization threshold and ensure that all future acquisitions of properties below the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00 will be recorded in accordance with COA Circular 2020-006;
Ensure that depreciation is properly provided for each class of PPE as discussed in PAG3 of the IPSAS 17 and provide for the detailed schedule of depreciation;
Prepare the JEV to reclassify the PPEs amounting to ₱9,639,657.27 to appropriate accounts; and
Prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE accounts.
Require the General Services Officer - Designate to prepare and maintain property cards for PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office; and
Create an Inventory Committee, who are temporarily relieved of all their regular duties to complete the physical inventory in three months or less, and to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require all the revenue collectors to turn-over the full amount of their collections at the close of business day to the Municipal Treasurer-Designate and the latter be required to deposit intact all collections to the LGU depository bank;
Direct the Accountable Officers to ensure timely rendition of report and such other records or their equivalents, as may be prescribed by agency’s operating procedures, and to reconcile with the accounting records at least quarterly;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer-Designate to issue ORs to acknowledge receipts of collections from one fund to another and stop the issuance of ORs to acknowledge CTC remittance of Barangay Treasurers deputized to collect Municipal Tax;
Direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to prepare JEVs for all the transactions of the Municipality and correctly used the prescribed format for the CRJs; and
Provide accounting proficient support staff in the Accounting Unit to ensure that the mandatory reports are properly prepared and submitted within the reglementary period.
